.TH readfile 1F "5 Jul 1990" "SunOS 5.11" "FMLI Commands"
.SH NAME
readfile, longline \- reads file, gets longest line
.SH SYNOPSIS
.LP
.nf
\fBreadfile\fR \fIfilename\fR
.fi

.LP
.nf
\fBlongline\fR [\fIfilename\fR]
.fi

.SH DESCRIPTION
.sp
.LP
The \fBreadfile\fR function reads \fIfilename\fR and copies it to \fIstdout\fR. No translation of NEWLINE is done. It keeps track of the longest line it reads and if there is a subsequent call to \fBlongline\fR, the length of that line, including the NEWLINE character,  is returned.
.sp
.LP
The \fBlongline\fR function returns the length, including the NEWLINE character, of the longest line in \fIfilename\fR. If \fIfilename\fR is not specified, it uses the file named in the last call to \fBreadfile\fR.
.SH EXAMPLES
.LP
\fBExample 1 \fRTypical use of readfile and longline
.sp
.LP
Here is a typical use of \fBreadfile\fR and \fBlongline\fR in a text frame definition file:

.sp
.in +2
.nf
\fB   .
   .
   .
text="`readfile myfile`"
columns=`longline`
   .
   .
   .\fR
.fi
.in -2
.sp

